<subSubSection id="C62D5B2CE356733E671D712A3F7118A4" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="B035ADBCE27748BB45FC18F2E3E79906" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="20BFC92194AF53140DFA04CF438C889E" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
The status of this species has been questionable. 
<bibRefCitation id="07F6A2E62C186E0DCDB0B5E085CDE20C" author="Carmean, D" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Entomology" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="35 - 76" publicationUrl="doi: 10.1046/j.1365-3113.1998.00042.x" refId="B5" refString="Carmean, D, Kimsey, L, 1998. Phylogenetic revision of the parasitoid wasp family Trigonalidae (Hymenoptera). Systematic Entomology 23 (1): 35 - 76, doi: 10.1046/j.1365-3113.1998.00042.x" title="Phylogenetic revision of the parasitoid wasp family Trigonalidae (Hymenoptera)." url="doi: 10.1046/j.1365-3113.1998.00042.x" volume="23" year="1998">Carmean and Kimsey (1998)</bibRefCitation>
thought that it might be only a large form of 
<taxonomicName id="A2DFAF0597D0184F82B472E523885574" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hova">
<emphasis id="EBFFE8A3E7F74CF1177646C8E17D9DCC" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Orthogonalys hova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="88F4CBC6DB716C2DD83EC802BC40C6F8" author="Benoit, PLG" journalOrPublisher="Revue de Zoologie et de Botanique Africaines" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="141 - 147" refId="B1" refString="Benoit, PLG, 1951. La systematique des Trigonaloidae (Hym.) ethiopiens. Revue de Zoologie et de Botanique Africaines 44 (2): 141 - 147" title="La systematique des Trigonaloidae (Hym.) ethiopiens." volume="44" year="1951">Benoit (1951)</bibRefCitation>
described the species from a single female. He separated 
<taxonomicName id="2D12B0E2340D01C7F37C889D9929DC63" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1951" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigantea">
<emphasis id="5F832CEA0C3401980B62E067729B0777" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Orthogonalys gigantea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="2F10CC165DD17C05A50862E7508915A5" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hova">
<emphasis id="2FA71C61B743DC26943F2149A4AF0102" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Orthogonalys hova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its large size (14 mm) and by the following: teeth of mandibles broad but not very long, the inferior tooth directed downwards; clypeus very thickened; antennal sockets closer together; punctation of scutellum sparser but stronger; propodeum broader than long, with transverse carinae complete and regular (not tangled and less strong); color identical except the white 
<normalizedToken id="D2B9B00309B74D88A5AE844A6C5749D3" originalValue="“atténué”">&quot;attenue&quot;</normalizedToken>
on the head and sides of abdomen. We have not seen additional females but have 
<pageBreakToken id="43D1A98139D5E5D2F1F1E65611609509" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" start="start">examined</pageBreakToken>
one male that compares in color and structure with the holotype female and was collected not far from the type locality, and we consider them to be the same species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7565BBA5808F96FB236C7A7572D473BE" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
After study of both sexes, we note a number of characters that justify treating 
<taxonomicName id="B764041E61D50B10DAD5DC4DCB55145B" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1951" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigantea">
<emphasis id="68EB654DCBCD7EF8739F5C442108FC94" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Orthogonalys gigantea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a valid species. Size cannot be regarded as a valid character in trigonalids. However, in comparison to 
<taxonomicName id="81FD3160ED281E7381E9BD25295B2354" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hova">
<emphasis id="691D2CAE121189D446AFD946C1884E81" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Orthogonalys hova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the specimens examined are consistently larger. The female holotype of 
<taxonomicName id="3125796E7B81BE81497A02B118EF5F57" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1951" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigantea">
<emphasis id="80B7FABA9F40974E8CED5732EE2527F8" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Orthogonalys gigantea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 14 mm and the male is 15 mm, whereas the largest 
<taxonomicName id="4EE2FE17330B0628A822050B741066CA" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hova">
<emphasis id="385123575836263E86150740135A9A92" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Orthogonalys hova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
female is 9 mm and males 5.0-9.5 mm, with most in the 7 mm range. We are not sure about the clypeus, mandible, punctation of the scutellum, and closeness of the antennal sockets as Benoit described; these do not seem significant. However, we emphasize the following characters: the sculpture of the propodeum of 
<taxonomicName id="08F30A75182A563482C4B52EF56E41E5" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1951" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigantea">
<emphasis id="3504B328354C7A256DBD8C5957B33536" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Orthogonalys gigantea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more transverse (
<figureCitation id="CFC8F1DC1960CE57EEA7A8F812AF3CA8" captionStart="Figures 10–13" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 10 - 13. Orthogonalys gigantea. 10 Mesosoma, dorsal view, male. 11 Head front view, female holotype. 12 Head, dorsal view, female holotype. 13 Male paramere, lateral view (appearance is due to hairs matted against the surface)." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11360" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) than the more reticulate sculpture of 
<taxonomicName id="84FD43C1B79CEA9C4C7A6DA6FAA468D2" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hova">
<emphasis id="AE28E93AA8C36495B2ED958235ABDEF8" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Orthogonalys hova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="645530D81AC8E79A2C1C317EBC2475ED" captionStart="Figures 16–20" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 16 - 20. Orthogonalys hova, male. 16 Mesosoma, dorsal view. 17 Head, front view. 18, Head, dorsal view. 19 Genitalia, dorsal view. 20 Apex of abdomen and genitalia, lateral view." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11362" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) and other 
<taxonomicName id="87EDA27A9708C21C40EE01600C3907F7" authorityName="Schulz" authorityYear="1905" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8D0EE7B7C1095E41A4D63503D2A3BBB6" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Orthogonalys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species; the color of both are similar, except that 
<taxonomicName id="663EF8CF0944D5A1C92AE6F2D818707C" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1951" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigantea">
<emphasis id="2F404E72D2DFE6A0E8D1FA67A168471F" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Orthogonalys gigantea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the metascutellum yellow and the male has the metasomal tergites mostly black whereas the metascutellum of 
<taxonomicName id="435843AB5E8BDF7129B9B06FC213BC2C" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hova">
<emphasis id="9FA3080FDE9CC61B6FDED816BA47F5FD" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Orthogonalys hova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is orange and the metasomal tergites of the male are considerably orange; and the parameres of 
<taxonomicName id="DC8EAD7D4AD0059E7F764E6C5571BB4F" authorityName="Benoit" authorityYear="1951" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigantea">
<emphasis id="7921850204DE108F450ABA04211EAE80" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Orthogonalys gigantea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are dark orange and rounded at the apex (
<figureCitation id="24BD27551C0532308FAD9239125261D9" captionStart="Figures 10–13" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 10 - 13. Orthogonalys gigantea. 10 Mesosoma, dorsal view, male. 11 Head front view, female holotype. 12 Head, dorsal view, female holotype. 13 Male paramere, lateral view (appearance is due to hairs matted against the surface)." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11360" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
), whereas those of 
<taxonomicName id="BEE961355B8F35E8B8719BB9B7C3DEBB" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hova">
<emphasis id="D8A3C796EED0F9056DF0A9E61FCB044C" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Orthogonalys hova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are white and more acute at the apex (
<figureCitation id="D695BA4AF734D13A5307475713E9DB5A" captionStart="Figures 16–20" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 16 - 20. Orthogonalys hova, male. 16 Mesosoma, dorsal view. 17 Head, front view. 18, Head, dorsal view. 19 Genitalia, dorsal view. 20 Apex of abdomen and genitalia, lateral view." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11362" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4C09DDDFE546901E2BC6790A53D47B88" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">This species is known only from northern Madagascar. The holotype and associated male were collected in the same area, around Diego Suarez, the two localities only about 50 km apart.</paragraph>
